title: Robot Lawn Mower front wheel / support wheel

description.text:
I use an old tianchen lawn mower. After lots of customizations like new main board, new software (visit www.ardumower.de) and new blade disks, I found that the robot is really loud when wheels roll over stones like small paths.

The main reason for this horrible sound are the rock hard front wheels and the bad bearings of them.

Because I had some 2K silicone laying around, I created this silicone mold to create new, soft wheels with new bearings which make really no noise. The wheels fits perfect on my Tianchen mower and might fit on others too.

The picture above shows two wheels made of silicone (yes, the red one is also silicone)

You need to print

1x Top mold
1x Bottom mold
2x inner part (kern)

You need some additional things:

  1. approx. 80g of 2k silicone, I ordered mine at www.trollfactory.de
  2. two bearings of type 6000 ZZ
  3. Screws M3 to combine the inner parts to one part (screws will become part of wheel)
  4. Screws or zip ties to close the mold (can be reused later)
  5. syringe, mixing pot, and some other household stuff

Printer:

Sparkcube

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

It doesn't matter which material you use. Also the resolution and infill rate doesn't matter. Its pretty easy to print

Its pretty reasy and done in a few steps (see pictures):

  1. put the 6000 ZZ bearings into the inner part
  2. use M3 screws to screw the two inner parts together
  3. Take the bottom part and insert the inner part. You may use some piece of treaded rods, screws or something else to keep it centered
  4. Attach the upper part of mold and screw everything together so it can't move
  5. Now it's time to prepare your silicone. You need approx. 80g in total
  6. Use a syringe to fill the mold with silicone
  7. wait several hours
  8. open the mold and replace your old, poor wheel with this selfmade super silent one.

Hello! And welcome to my most ambitious model and print yet.

The (unofficial) Star Wars Rebellion organizer!

This print has been designed to hold every single ship, card, token, and die that comes with Fantasy Flights Star-Wars in a box. (I lied, there actually isn’t enough room for ALL of the damage token. But in the handful of games we’ve played, we’ve never used more than six tokens at once)

FEATURES!
-Card/hand holders along the front of both players cabinets
-Deck holders for every different deck of cards used during play
-Individual token organizers
-Dice separators and storage
-Shelf space for starting game collection of miniatures
-Pull-and-play storage for quick setup and teardown

I highly recommend that if you want to use this print, that you fabricate some sort of Foamcore (or other material) that’s the same height as the box itself. As well as walls that keep the shelves closed against the cabinets. That, or just use some tape. The tolerances for all the shelves were kept loose due to printing troubles.

This print has three main bodies.
-Rebel Cabinet
-Imperial Cabinet
-Battle (dice) cabinet

This is broken down various easy-to-print pieces. (sized for the Prusa Mk2 and like bed size)
-Rebel cabinet base

Everything but the shelves needs to be glued together, notches and slots have been built into the design to guide this.

The prints that I have made, and are shown in the pictures above are of a previous version than the models uploaded. The models I had printed were not separated for easier printing, and did not have the token organizers printed into them. But all dimensions should be the same. If there are any problems, please let me know.

I know there’s an upcoming expansion to this game, I’m not sure if I will be making an expansion add on cabinet(s) to accommodate.

description.text:

  • Easy assembling and disassembling making it easy to travel with.
  • Easy to scale/size the model due to the use of equations.

Configurations:

  • Grolsch
  • Heineken
  • Jupiler
  • Nuka Cola
  • Reijen Breweries (my own brand)

Tools required

Check the assembly or bill of materials to see which parts are needed to be cut. When you decide to scale the model when you convert the drawings to adobe illustrator files. I recommend using this method. www.youtube.com/watch?v=hZrGLonrpt8&t=191s

Two models from other engineers are used in this build.
Bottlecap by Raian Nur Islam

Special thanks to Tom Wittebrood (Avans Hogeschool) for making the bottlecap animation.

Please let me know when you decide to make on for yourself I love to see your versions.

Want to buy one? You can. Just send me a message on Grabcad and I try to respond as quickly as I can. I could also add a few custom engravings to the model. The price of the Drinko Plinko depends on how far it needs to be shipped.

title: 3rd Z-Axis Stepper Parts for D-Bot
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a pair of parts I designed / modified for D-Bot derived printers that will add a 3rd z-axis threaded rod connected to a 3rd stepper motor. The motor mount is a clone (or as close as I could get) to the D-Bot, so another print of the stock one would probably work fine. The bed mount is a from-scratch mount that fits the stock threaded rod nut (and anti-backlash, if used) but moves the nut farther out from the bed so it can align properly with a stepper mounted below it. The nut can mount either inserted into the body of the bracket, or inverted (as it is in my photo). The inverted position is still supported around it by a flange, and allows room for the anti-backlash nut to fit. The whole setup can mount either inside or outside the rear rails of the printer. I've ran it both ways, but moved it to the rear to avoid any potential snags from my bed wiring.

A lot of 3-support mechanisms (or customized 2-support) others have put together on here were focused on using toothed gears and belts to synchronize two or three threaded rods to a single stepper motor. While that mechanism works, it has some significant drawbacks, including the situation where a belt slips, making it far more complicated to get the Z axis back into alignment. It also leaves an exposed belt under the printer where things can catch on and potentially damage.

Using a 3rd stepper motor avoids those issues by driving all three rods equally. Depending on your controller, you may be able to run all three in parallel or serial off your controller. (I'm using a Duet Wifi, and run all three in serial.)

This is a forward-looking design in that I can add a Duet2x or 5x controller and go to three-way active bed leveling, where the controller drives each Z axis separately to live level the bed.

To keep the three steppers in precise sync long-term, I've got the printer calibrated to re-sync them at power up. The basic pattern is to have the printer home all three axis first. Then it lowers the bed 310mm quickly. At that point, it does two things -- it reduces the stepper current to a very low amount, and then does a slow additional move of 30mm. The build platform gantry catches on end-stops screwed on each stepper mount, causing the stepper in question to start skipping. Letting all three start skipping ensures all three go back into precise sync above the steppers. At that point, it cranks the stepper power back up and z-homes again.

For those interested in doing something similar, I have a corresponding part that bolts onto the top of the D-Bot motor mounts (including this one, which is a clone of it) that stops the gantry at precisely 40mm above the stepper motor mount. You can see it here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2510053

title: Anet A6 Motor Bracket and Frame Stabilizer
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
ENGLISH
I'm printing and designing several parts to increase the stiffness of ANET A6 frame to improve the printing stability. Recently, I noticed a bending in main frame at motor mount corners, causing a little deviation in X axis.

This bending is proportional to X belt tension (needed to obtain good prints), which is driven through linear guide and finally to frame. When Z position is far away from the zero, this bending is mainly absorbed by the linear rod by slaightly bending itself, but when Z is near to zero or maximum position, the linear guide cannot be bent due to the short distance, and therefore it bends the frame at weakest points, which are the corners of central frame.

These brackets fix both motor mounts and main frame to a platform and no more bending was observed, increasing the printing quality at lowest layers (where bending was more noticeable). Moreover, it is also a dust cover for motor and it looks great (at least for me :D).

These parts have been designed to be slided from the side of the printer because in my case it requires much work to disassemble the other brackets I have. You only have to remove three motor screws, the linear guide and the rear screw which fixes the motor mount to main frame. After that, you can slide this part and mount all together again (nuts position have been hollowed to avoid any misalignment). Obviously you need to anchor the bracket to a platform through M4 countersunk screws to make it sense. Screws I've used to fix all are:
-Motor screws: M3x15 mm
-Rear frame screw: M3x25mm
-Motor mount screw (which fixes upper plate of motor and the foot): M3x20 mm

I've included a center cut out to allow the access to screws of coupler.

I highly recommend to anchor the printer in several parts, it is much more precise and stable producing better prints. Moreover, you can print two handles which will allow you to transport or move for printer service easily. I have printed this bracket in conjunction with the following parts obtaining a stiffer setup:
-https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1896013
-https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2501888

I printed it with following parameters using 52 grams of material:
-Layer height: 0.25mm
-No supports if printed as seen in images.
-Infill: cubic subdivision and 30%
-3 shell walls
-PLA (PETG preferred)
-Horizontal expansion: -0.1 mm (this is for my printer, which is the main deviation, you can adjust according to your calibration)

If you have any question or suggestion don't doubt to comment!

Hope you enjoy!

ESPAÑOL

Estoy imprimiendo y diseñando varias piezas para aumentar la rigidez del marco de la ANET A6 para mejorar la estabilidad de impresión. Hace poco me dí cuenta de que el marco principal se doblaba en las esquinas donde se monta el motor, causando una pequeña desviación en el eje X.

Esta flexión es proporcional a la tensión de la correa X (necesaria para obtener buenas impresiones), que se propaga a través de la guía lineal y finalmente al bastidor. Cuando la posición Z está muy lejos del cero, esta curvatura es absorbida principalmente por la barra lineal flexionándose ligeramente, pero cuando el eje Z está cerca de la posición cero o máxima, la guía lineal no puede doblarse debido a la distancia que hay tan pequeña, y por lo tanto, dobla el marco en los puntos más débiles, que son las esquinas del marco central.

Estas escuadras fijan los soportes del motor y el bastidor principal a una plataforma, evitando que se doble, aumentando la calidad de impresión en las capas más bajas (donde la flexión era más grande). Por otra parte, también es una cubierta de polvo para el motor y estéticamente queda mejor (al menos para mí: D).

Estas piezas están diseñadas para ser deslizadas desde el lado de la impresora porque en mi caso requiere mucho trabajo desmontar los otros soportes que tengo. Sólo hay que quitar tres tornillos de motor, la guía lineal y el tornillo trasero que fija el pie del motor al bastidor principal. Después, se desliza la pieza desde el lateral y se monta todo de nuevo (la posición de las tuercas se han vaciado para evitar cualquier obstáculo). Obviamente, es necesario anclar el soporte a una plataforma mediante tornillos avellanados M4 para que tenga sentido. Los tornillos que he usado para fijar todo son:
-Tornillos de motor: M3x15 mm
-Tornillo de marco trasero: M3x25mm
-Tornillo de montaje del motor (que fija la placa superior del motor y el pie): M3x20 mm

Recomiendo encarecidamente anclar la impresora en varias partes, es mucho más preciso y estable, dando mejores acabados a las impresiones. Además, se pueden imprimir dos asas que permiten transportar o mover fácilmente para hacerle el mantenimiento o instalar mejoras. He impreso este soporte junto con las siguientes partes obteniendo una configuración más rígida:
-https://www.thingiverse.com/thing: 1896013
-https://www.thingiverse.com/thing: 2501888

Lo imprimí con los siguientes parámetros consumiendo 52 gramos:
- Altura de la capa: 0.25mm
-Sin soportes si se imprime como se ve en las imágenes.
-Infill: subdivisión cúbica y 30%
-3 paredes
-PLA (PETG sería mejor)
-Expansión horizontal: -0.1 mm (esto es para mi impresora, que es la desviación que he medido, ajustar según calibración)

No dudes en comentar si tienes cualquier duda o sugerencia.

¡Espero que lo disfrutes!

description.text:
Inspiration for my lack enclosure came from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2226678, the printed legs and corner caps are as the original design although updated to accept 3mm material.

What I Used:
• Two Ikea Lack tables
• 500x500 mm plexiglass panel for front
• 1x sheet 1829x3x607 sheet of MDF (used the cut the other 3 sides from)
• 4x printed feet (as uploaded STL file)
• 4x Printed tops (as uploaded STL file)
• 1x Printed filament guide (as uploaded STL file)
• 1x acrylic 250mm 5 sided cube (brought from http://www.plasticsforyou.co.uk/250mm_5_Side_Cube_Box_display_stand_clear_acrylic_p/5sc250mm.htm)
• 2x 120mm computer fans
• 2x Printed fan locking rings (as uploaded STL file)
• 2x Printed fan cap (as uploaded STL file)
• 1x Printed fan duct cap (accepts 100mm ducting) (as uploaded STL file)
• 1x length of 100mm air ducting (length depends on your requirements
• LED lights (optional)

Assembley:

First build 1x lack table and add the 4x printed feet to the table legs, and the 4x tops to each corner of the the table top. Use the table top from the second table (legs optional) as the base and sit printed feet over each corner of the base.

Next cut MDF & plexiglass to size and istall weather stripping (if required) to close any gaps between table and side panels. I then cut two circle in one of the side and installed the 120mm fans (1x intake at bottom, 1x exhaust at top) I installed the intake near the electronics of the printer so I could keep some cool air on them (doesn’t really effect the temp inside the enclosure to much, this can always be closed off by using a printed cap should you need a higher temp like when printing ABS). I re-wired the computer fans to run off a standard USB plug adapter although fans are 12v I am running on a 9v adapter which means they run almost silent (slightly slower) but move enough air for my needs.

I then cut the lack table top (using a craft knife) and install the filament guide to run filament through the table top. I then used the 250mm acrylic cube as a filament enclosure which simply sits on the top of the enclosure and can hold two spools. I attached some weather stripping to the bottom of the cube to create an air seal to the lack table top.

I then lastly installed some LED lighting to the underside of the table as the enclosure was getting dark with 3x solid sides. You could of course use plexiglass for all sides but in my case 3 of the sides aren't really going be that visible so i opted for the cheaper MDF sides.

Currently a work in progress almost complete, just waiting on the arrival of the plexiglass (currently using a towel to close front off), MDF sides will be sprayed satin black. I will update item when complete.

UPDATE

So after using the enclosure for awhile now rather than paint the MDF sides as originally planned i've installed sound proofing foam. I did this to dampen the vibration noise i was experiencing it will also help with enclosure temps.

Foam from Amazon https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B0045Z94EY/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Resolution:

0.2

Notes:

• Lack feet printed – No supports
• Lack tops printed – No supports
• Filament guide – No supports
• Fan locking rings – Supports required
• Fan caps – Supports required (only for locking knubs)
• Fan duct cap – Supports required (only for locking knubs)

title: Poor man's HVLP spray gun canister Campbell Hausfeld Husky

description.text:
9/1/17
Fixed Bottle2Bottle_coupler and made it more printer friendly.

8/31/17

Because dropping $8.99 on a new canister for your recently purchased second-hand sprayer is not your style! Print this coupler and stick-it to the man. All it takes: two $1.99 water bottles and $1.00 plumber's tape.

Works great.

Tapered threads.

Tested on a Campbell Hausfeld sprayer, but noticed identical canisters on Husky sprayers. Sprayer thread size is 5/8 Fine American Standard size (or M16 with a 1.5mm pitch).

Instructions:

Step 1.
Find 2 water bottles with a 27mm thread diameter. Think: Aquafina, Dasani, DejaBlue, 20fl oz Mountain Dew. Heck, even a 2L Pepsi bottle will do.

Step 2.
Cut entire bottom of one bottle to make funnel. After making funnel, use Bottle2Bottle_coupler to tighten funnel onto second water bottle. Then, pour paint onto second water bottle.

Step 3.
Remove Bottle2Bottle_coupler from water bottles and tighten Bottle_Paint_Gun_coupler to bottle containing paint.

Step 4.
Tighten bottle with the Bottle_Paint_Gun_coupler onto paint gun.

Step 5.
Use knife and slash a breather hole onto top of water bottle before spraying.

  • Don't forget to use plumber's tape for steps 2,3 and 4! These water bottles have non sealing threads and leak with out plumber's tape!

title: NodeMCU DHT11 Temperature + Humidity Sensor Enclosure

description.text:
A simple enclosure and mount for a DHT11 temperature + humidity sensor and a NodeMCU. This project is designed around the HiLetgo NodeMCU board available on Amazon but should fit most similar designs.

The NodeMCU is mounted with the face exposed to maximize WIFI signal strength and heat dissipation, and to reduce the effect on the sensor's temperature readings.

Below the NodeMCU is a chamber sized to hold wires with enough clearance for Dupont connectors to connect to the header pins. The base is divided into two chambers for additional thermal isolation, with a vented chamber for the sensor.

Two slots are provided on the lid to fasten the USB power cable with a zip tie, and a flange is included on the base for hanging or screw mounting, though it will work just as well sitting flat on a table or shelf.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Doesn't Matter

No

Notes:

Rotate parts in the slicer so flat sides are down; the lid has four risers that should be printed facing up.

It is recommended to print the lid by itself first to check that the NodeMCU and USB power cable fit properly before printing the base.

A video of the base being printed is available on YouTube.

Additional Materials

  • 4 bolts, M3 size, 12mm or longer
  • 1 zip tie.

Recommended

  • 3 female-female Dupont jumper cables

Optional

  • Hot glue

Assembly

Lid

Loosely thread the bolts to align the NodeMCU on the lid, then plug in the USB cable. Holding the NodeMCU flush against the lid, thread the zip tie through the two slots and tighten to secure the cable. Attach wires for the sensor to the appropriate pins on the NodeMCU.

Base

With the lid assembly and the base, thread the loose wire ends through the slot in the wall of the base that is between the NodeMCU chamber and the vented sensor chamber. Attach the sensor to the appropriate loose ends of the wire, then pull and coil excess cable in the NodeMCU chamber. If you used Dupont cables, you can optionally hot glue the plastic headers to the slot in the wall to keep the sensor from moving around.

Final Assembly

Place the lid on top of the base, aligning the bolts with the holes, and tighten the bolts gradually in an X pattern until everything is snug. Take care not to over torque and strip the holes with the threads.

Printing and assembly tips

Printing tips
1-As with most of my models, no supports are required.

2-Be sure to clean any first layer squish if you have any problem joining parts. The parts should fit nicely when printed cleanly or with a slight first layer squish.

3-I did not require any rafts or brims for any of the parts.

..
Assembly tips:
1-The eyebrows have the thinner part pointing toward the nose. The parts are small and print well but if for some reason you have an issue inserting them into the head (over-extrusion or a squish that cannot be cleaned) simply flip them over and put them in with the flat side facing out.

2-The left/right eyes are interchangeable. There is an up/down positioning of each eye. If it does not look right when inserted just rotate the eye piece for a better fit.

4-Since I model with the goal of no supports, the angle of the left arm did not allow for a dent into the shirt. This is not really an issue here, just glue the left arm to the shirt sleeve and an extra dab of glue on his hand were it touches the stripe.

5-Refer to the assembly diagram for putting the model together. The model is meant to be glued.

Use the "Enclosure - Panel - Solid" file if you want to print an end panel without any cutouts (such as if you didn't have an LCD board, or wanted the LCD ribbon cables to route the same direction as the stepper driver cables). description.text:
This is my custom design Snakebite stand for CaseStudyno8's Darksaber.

The stand uses the weight of the Darksaber's long grip to hold the emitter guard against the stand's fangs, suspending the saber at a upward angle and showing off as much of the saber from as possible.

The multi-sectioned base allows it to be printed on smaller printer beds and with different colors and types of filament. In the display photos above, I used wood filament, finished with a light Jarrah wood stain to get the rich dark cherry color.

I used two-part Gorilla Glue to assemble this display stand. Remember that this is a resin epoxy that tends to set in a matter of minutes, so don't use very much and make sure to wipe away excess before then.

description.text:
Filament tube feeders and tube holder for a filament spool dry box.

I used these connectors: https://www.amazon.com/Witbot-Straight-Pneumatic-Connector-Long-Distance/dp/B01KHN1HWY

The feeder was designed in Tinkercad so the resolution is not great (mesh triangles along curves). The holder is fine.

When the filament tubes are not in use the ends plug into the holder. You should be able to keep enough filament out of the end of the tube in the holder that you'll be able to pull filament through the tube later.

Can be used with or without the backs inside the box. The backs do help keep everything fully pressed and flat against the box walls though.

Attach to box with M3x16mm screws and (nyloc) nuts.
Push in connectors screw directly into the parts.
Use with 4mm OD PTFE tube.

Grab the wood.py script. Run it with:

Min Temp: as low as your filament can go.

Once printed, sand it with the grain with 100 grit up to 220 grit. The goal is to remove the cylindrical bumpiness of the individual layers until you have a mostly flat surface. If you don't get it flat enough here, the finish will make it overly shiny -- compare the picture with two of them in it.

Then stain. I used Minwax English Chestnut. I left the stain on for ~12hr before wiping off what was left.

Then finish. I used Minwax Polyurethane Satin. Follow the instructions on the can, but be very careful about sanding that first application because the color stain does not penetrate even a single layer and you will remove it incredibly quick.
